      <hedline>
        <hl1>Applying RICO To Civil Cases</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Application of federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) in lawsuit filed by California Medical Association against insurance companies discussed (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The lawsuit filed by the California Medical Association is an effort to apply the civil provisions of the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, or RICO. The statute is best known for its use in criminal cases in which the government charges that groups like organized crime or gangs have engaged in a pattern of conspiratorial activity to further their crimes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The lawsuit filed by the California Medical Association is an effort to apply the civil provisions of the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, or RICO. The statute is best known for its use in criminal cases in which the government charges that groups like organized crime or gangs have engaged in a pattern of conspiratorial activity to further their crimes.</p>
        <p>In civil lawsuits, plaintiffs like the doctors' group use the civil provisions of the RICO statute to contend that they have been economically harmed through a pattern of misconduct. If successful under a RICO claim, they can win up to three times the amount of damages that they would in a traditional lawsuit.</p>
      </block>
